Git Commands

1. git init
This command initializes a repository in the current working directory locally
syntax: git init

2. git clone
This comand clones and downloads a pre-existing repository on github to the current working directory
syntax: git clone <url>
example: git clone https://github.com/kartik11721/test_repo

3. git status
This command checks for any differences between the master branch to the current committed file
syntax: git status

4. git commit
This command records the changes in the repository
syntax: git commit
example: git commit -m "Commit Message"

5. git add
This command prepares the content for the next commit
syntax: git add <file_name>
example: git add . (where . represents all files in directory)
	 git add README.md
	 
5. git push
This command is used to transfer the changes from the local commit to the remote reposotory
syntax: git push

6. git pull
This command is used to transfer the changes from the remote reposotory ( on github ) to the local directory
syntax: git pull

